properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued March 7 at 11:20PM CST until March 10 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Mobile AL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Dangerous rip currents expected.

* WHERE...In Alabama, Mobile Coastal and Baldwin Coastal
Counties. In Florida, Escambia Coastal, Santa Rosa Coastal and
Okaloosa Coastal Counties.

* WHEN...From Friday evening through Sunday evening.

* IMPACTS...Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away
from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:
Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.areaDesc: Chittenden, VT
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 8 at 12:11AM EST until March 8 at 9:00AM EST by NWS Burlington VT
properties.description:
...The Flood Warning continues for the following rivers in Vermont...

Winooski River At Essex Junction affecting Chittenden County.

* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Winooski River at Essex Junction.

* WHEN...Until late this morning.

* IMPACTS...At 12.0 feet, Farms in the Burlington Intervale begin to
flood. Water will flood fields adjacent to North Williston Road in
Essex and will approach North Williston Road.
At 12.5 feet, North Williston Road in Essex will begin to flood,
and motorists should seek an alternate route.  Water will approach
low lying farmland in the Burlington Intervale.
At 13.0 feet, Water will cover North Williston Road in Essex and
Pine Island Road in Colchester. Low lying farmland in the
Burlington Intervale will flood.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 11:30 PM EST Thursday the stage was 13.0 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 11:30 PM EST Thursday was 13.4 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage
early this morning and continue falling to 7.1 feet early
Sunday afternoon.
- Flood stage is 12.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
13.7 feet on 04/16/2019.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Motorists should not attempt to drive around barricades or drive
cars through flooded areas.

Additional information is available at www.weather.gov.

The next statement will be issued this morning at 900 AM EST.

properties.areaDesc: Glades; Hendry; Inland Palm Beach County; Inland Collier County; Inland Broward County
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 7 at 11:09PM EST by NWS Miami FL
properties.description:
Areas of fog...some locally dense...are beginning to develop
across Interior portions of South Florida. Visibilities are
likely to be reduced to around 1 mile in general, with localized
areas experiencing reduced visibilities to one-half of a mile at
times. Fog will likely persist through the overnight and into the
morning commute. If lower visibilities materialize, a dense fog
advisory will be needed.

Motorists are advised to drive with caution tonight and Friday
morning as visibilities may widely vary over short distances. Use
low beam headlights and leave extra distance between your vehicle
and others on the road when encountering significant reductions in
visibility. Allow extra time to travel to destinations.

expected in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal
waterways.

* WHERE...The lower Cape Fear River including downtown
Wilmington.

* WHEN...From 6 AM to 9 AM EST Friday.

* IMPACTS...The lowest portions of USS North Carolina Road and
Battleship Road begin to observe minor coastal flooding. Water
begins to spread out of storm drains onto Water Street just
south of Market Street in downtown Wilmington.

average tide conditions. Additional locations may experience

properties.areaDesc: Majuro
properties.headline: High Surf Advisory issued March 8 at 2:03PM ChST until March 11 at 3:00PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the High Surf Advisory, Large breaking waves of 10 to 12
feet, building to 13 feet over the weekend. For the Coastal Flood
Statement, isolated minor coastal flooding expected.

* WHERE...North and east facing reefs of Majuro.

* WHEN...For the High Surf Advisory, until 3 PM ChST Monday. For the
Coastal Flood Statement, from this afternoon through Monday
afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Some water on low lying roads and property.
Dangerous swimming and surfing conditions and localized beach
erosion.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Surf is being supported by a large trade-wind
surge that extends eastward to Hawaii. With the upcoming King Tides
around March 10th, minor coastal inundation is expected starting
this afternoon, especially during high tide. Greatest risk will be
along shores exposed to the northeast to east across the Marshall
Islands since surf and tides will be higher around the Marshall
Islands. Please report any inundation to the local Weather Service
Office (WSO).
properties.instruction:
Do not drive through flooded roadways.

Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to
dangerous surf conditions.

properties.areaDesc: Majuro
properties.headline: Coastal Flood Statement issued March 8 at 2:03PM ChST until March 11 at 3:00PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the High Surf Advisory, Large breaking waves of 10 to 12
feet, building to 13 feet over the weekend. For the Coastal Flood
Statement, isolated minor coastal flooding expected.

* WHERE...North and east facing reefs of Majuro.

* WHEN...For the High Surf Advisory, until 3 PM ChST Monday. For the
Coastal Flood Statement, from this afternoon through Monday
afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Some water on low lying roads and property.
Dangerous swimming and surfing conditions and localized beach
erosion.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Surf is being supported by a large trade-wind
surge that extends eastward to Hawaii. With the upcoming King Tides
around March 10th, minor coastal inundation is expected starting
this afternoon, especially during high tide. Greatest risk will be
along shores exposed to the northeast to east across the Marshall
Islands since surf and tides will be higher around the Marshall
Islands. Please report any inundation to the local Weather Service
Office (WSO).
properties.instruction:
Do not drive through flooded roadways.

Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to
dangerous surf conditions.

properties.headline: Flash Flood Warning issued March 7 at 9:17PM CST until March 8 at 3:30AM CST by NWS Springfield MO
properties.description:
FFWSGF

The National Weather Service in Springfield has issued a

* Flash Flood Warning for...
Southeastern Barton County in southwestern Missouri...
Southern Dade County in southwestern Missouri...
Northeastern Jasper County in southwestern Missouri...
Northwestern Lawrence County in southwestern Missouri...

* Until 330 AM CST Friday.

* At 917 PM CST, Doppler radar indicated thunderstorms producing
heavy rain across the warned area. Between 1 and 2 inches of rain
have fallen. Flash flooding is ongoing or expected to begin
shortly.

HAZARD...Flash flooding caused by thunderstorms.

SOURCE...Radar.

IMPACT...Flash flooding of small creeks and streams, urban
areas, highways, streets and underpasses as well as
other poor drainage and low-lying areas.

* Some locations that will experience flash flooding include...
Carthage, Greenfield, Lockwood, Jasper, Golden City, Carytown,
South Greenfield, Dudenville, Meinert, Maple Grove, Red Oak,
Kenoma, Boston, Pennsboro and Stockton Lake.

This includes the following low water crossings...
Muddy Creek at Highway 126, Dry Fork at Pine Road, Sons Creek at
County Road 113, Sinking Creek at County Road 181 and Lousy Branch
at County Road 85.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Many flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

In hilly terrain there are hundreds of low water crossings which are
potentially dangerous in heavy rain. Do not attempt to cross flooded
roads. Find an alternate route.

deaths occur in vehicles.

Caution is urged when walking near riverbanks.

Additional information is available at www.weather.gov/gray.

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL EARLY SATURDAY MORNING

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 7 at 3:36PM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
properties.description:
A developing moisture band over the North Pacific will stream
northeast and into the panhandle starting mid next week. Rainfall
total are looking moderate to heavy with 24 hour totals in the 1
to 2 inch range. The main item to watch is a nose of warmer air
will move into the panhandle that will push freezing levels over
5000 feet across the southern panhandle and 1000 to 2000 over the
north central panhandle.

The item to keep an eye on is additional snow melt from warming
along with the rainfall of the heavier rainfall that stream flow
will have higher water levels. We will continue to maintain a
watch over this potential hazardous situation.

NWSheadline: WARMING AND PERIODS HEAVIER RAIN MID NEXT WEEK

properties.headline: Marine Weather Statement issued March 7 at 3:04PM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
properties.description:
Northerly to northeasterly winds in combination with frigid,
Arctic air could lead to extreme vessel icing at rates of 4 cm an
hour or greater.

As cold air moves south from the Arctic beginning Friday, heavy
to extreme freezing spray will spread south and east from Saint
Matthew Island. Expect heavy to extreme freezing spray to reach
Kuskokwim Delta coastal waters by Saturday and Bristol Bay coastal
waters by Monday. The threat of extreme freezing spray could
persist as late as midweek.

Operating a vessel in heavy to extreme freezing spray is
hazardous. Freezing spray may render mechanical and electronic
components inoperable. Rapid ice accretion on decks and
superstructures may result in catastrophic loss of stability.

properties.areaDesc: Rutland, VT
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 7 at 7:02PM EST until March 9 at 9:00AM EST by NWS Burlington VT
properties.description:
...The Flood Warning is extended for the following rivers in
Vermont...

Otter Creek At Center Rutland affecting Rutland County.

* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Otter Creek at Center Rutland.

* WHEN...Until late Saturday morning.

* IMPACTS...At 7.0 feet, There will be field flooding along Otter
Creek from Clarendon downstream to Pittsford.
At 8.0 feet, Low lying portions of South Creek Road will flood in
Clarendon between Walker Mountain Road and Wallingford. In
Pittsford, Elm Street and Depot Road will be under water. Field
flooding will occur along Dorr Drive in Rutland, along with
lowland flooding upstream to Wallingford and downstream to
Pittsford.
At 9.0 feet, In Clarendon, low lying portions of South Creek Rd.
will flood between Walker Mountain Rd. and Wallingford, and water
will approach Alfrecha Rd. In Pittsford, Elm St. and Depot Hill
Rd. will begin to flood. Field flooding will occur along Dorr Dr.
in Rutland, along with lowland flooding upstream to Wallingford
and downstream to Pittsford.
At 10.0 feet, In Rutland, flooding will occur on low lying roads
including Dorr Drive, Park Street and Clement Road. High water
will also approach Meadow Street and the adjacent recreation
fields will flood. Alfrecha Road in Clarendon will flood. Water
will approach homes on West Proctor Road near Route 4 in Rutland.
Downstream in Proctor and Pittsford, numerous roads will flood,
along with Route 73 west of Brandon.
At 11.0 feet, Water will come near homes and businesses in Rutland
along Otter Creek on Dorr Dr., Park St., Meadow St., Clement Rd.,
and along the confluence of Otter Creek and the Clarendon River at
West Proctor Rd. and Rte 4. Low lying roads in Clarendon and
Wallingford will flood. Downstream in Proctor and Pittsford,
numerous roads will be inundated, including Elm St., Willow St.
and Depot Hill Road. Route 73 west of Brandon will flood.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 6:45 PM EST Thursday the stage was 9.7 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 6:45 PM EST Thursday was 9.7 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 9.8
feet just after midnight tonight. It will then fall below
flood stage tomorrow afternoon.
- Flood stage is 8.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
9.7 feet on 12/26/2020.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Motorists should not attempt to drive around barricades or drive
cars through flooded areas.

Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Additional information is available at www.weather.gov.

The next statement will be issued Friday morning at 915 AM EST.

properties.areaDesc: Coastal waters from Cape Foulweather to Florence OR out 10 nm; Waters from Cape Foulweather to Florence OR from 10 to 60 nm
properties.headline: Gale Watch issued March 7 at 3:33PM PST until March 9 at 4:00AM PST by NWS Portland OR
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Small Craft Advisory, seas 7 to 10 ft at 10
seconds and south winds 20 to 25 kt with gusts up to 30 kt
expected. For the Gale Watch, seas 10 to 13 ft at 13 seconds and
south winds 20 to 30 kt with gusts up to 40 kt possible.

* WHERE...Coastal waters from Cape Foulweather to Florence OR
out 10 NM and Waters from Cape Foulweather to Florence OR from
10 to 60 NM.

* WHEN...Small Craft Advisory, from 1 PM to 10 PM PST Friday.
Gale Watch, from Friday evening through late Friday night.

* IMPACTS...Strong winds can cause hazardous seas which could
capsize or damage vessels and reduce visibility.
properties.instruction:
A Gale Watch is issued when the risk of gale force winds of 34 to
47 knots has significantly increased, but the specific timing
and/or location is still uncertain. It is intended to provide
additional lead time for mariners who may wish to consider
altering their plans.

properties.areaDesc: Columbia River Bar
properties.headline: Small Craft Advisory issued March 7 at 3:33PM PST until March 9 at 4:00PM PST by NWS Portland OR
properties.description:
* WHAT...Rough bar conditions expected. Seas 6 to 8 ft Friday
evening, building to 11 to 13 ft Saturday morning

* WHERE...In the Main Channel of the Columbia River Bar.

* WHEN...From 1 PM Friday to 4 PM PST Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Conditions will be hazardous to small craft,
especially when operating near to, or attempting to cross, the
Columbia River Bar.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Strong ebb current of 5.71 kt at 219 PM
Thursday. Ebb current of 3.84 kt at 257 AM Friday. Strong ebb
current of 6.2 kt at 310 PM Friday.
properties.instruction:
A Small Craft Advisory means that wave conditions are expected to
be hazardous to small craft in the vicinity of the Columbia River
Bar. Mariners are advised to obtain the latest bar conditions
from the United States Coast Guard before attempting to cross the
bar.

NWSheadline: SMALL CRAFT ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 1 PM FRIDAY TO 4 PM PST SATURDAY

properties.description:

Passes starting on Saturday and continuing through Tuesday.

NWSheadline: Very Cold This Weekend Into Early Next Week

properties.areaDesc: South Slopes of the Western Brooks Range; Noatak Valley; Kivalina and Red Dog Dock; Lower Kobuk Valley; Baldwin Peninsula; Northern Seward Peninsula; Upper Kobuk Valleys; Shishmaref; Bering Strait Coast; Southern Seward Peninsula Coast; Interior Seward Peninsula; Eastern Norton Sound and Nulato Hills; Yukon Delta Coast; Lower Yukon River; St Lawrence Island; Lower Koyukuk Valley; Middle Yukon Valley; Lower Yukon and Innoko Valleys
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 7 at 2:00PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
properties.description:
A deep arctic trough will move south over the Western Interior and
West Coast and bring well below normal temperatures beginning
Friday night. Low temperatures by Saturday morning will be in the
teens and 20s below zero and remain that way through Wednesday
morning. Highs will range from near zero to 10 below. North winds
of 10 to 30 mph with higher gusts in normally channeled areas
including Shaktoolik, Johnson's Camp, and the Bering Strait are
expected starting Friday night and lasting through the middle of
next week as well. This, combined with lows dropping into the
teens and 20s below zero, will bring wind chills into the 20s to
40s below zero by Friday night, with widepread wind chills of 35
to 45 below zero by Monday morning.

Residents and those traveling in the area are encouraged to be
prepared for much colder than normal conditions.

NWSheadline: Cold Temperatures And Wind Chills Beginning Friday Night

properties.areaDesc: West Central Highlands; Glorieta Mesa Including Glorieta Pass; Northern Sangre de Cristo Mountains; Sandia/Manzano Mountains Including Edgewood; South Central Mountains
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 7 at 3:59PM MST by NWS Albuquerque NM
properties.description:
An upper level disturbance will work together with a backdoor cold
front to produce an area of snow showers midday Friday through
late Friday night along the spine of the central mountain chain
and the Continental Divide. Locally higher snowfall rates of 1 to
2 inches an hour along with reduced visibility could be possible
in any heavier showers. Snow showers should quickly taper off
early Saturday morning as overall lift and moisture decreases.

NWSheadline: ACCUMULATING SNOW TO IMPACT MOUNTAIN AND HIGH TERRAIN TRAVEL LATE FRIDAY MORNING INTO FRIDAY NIGHT

.Heavy snow beginning tonight will move into the Haines and Haines
Highway area. Warm moisture will overrun cooler air at the
surface, producing heavy snow and raising snow levels over time.
As the warm air moves over Haines, snow will become increasingly
wet and heavy, limiting snow totals. For areas 600 feet and above,
such as Haines Customs, precipitation is expected to stay as snow
and accumulate up to 12 inches.

* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 8 to 12
inches.

* WHERE...Haines Highway above 600 ft.

* WHEN...From midnight tonight to midnight AKST Friday night.

* IMPACTS...Travel will be very difficult and is discouraged.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Highest snowfall rates around Haines
Customs is expected to be Friday morning with rates around 0.5
to 0.75 inches per hour.
properties.instruction:
If you must travel, keep an extra flashlight, food, and water
with you in case of an emergency.

People are urged to prepare their property before the onset of
winter weather.

For the latest road conditions, where available, call 5 1 1 or
visit 511.alaska.gov.

properties.description:
...A FIRE WEATHER WATCH IS IN EFFECT FRIDAY LATE MORNING AND
AFTERNOON FOR LOCATIONS ALONG AND WEST OF INTERSTATE HIGHWAY
69C...

.A dry cold front ushers in rapidly lowering relative humidity
and moderate to gusty winds elevating the fire danger for
potential rapid growth and spread of any wildfires that may get
started.

Zone 249 Jim Hogg, Fire Weather Zone 250 Brooks, Fire Weather
Zone 252 Starr, Fire Weather Zone 253 Southern Hidalgo and
Fire Weather Zone 353 Northern Hidalgo.

* TIMING...11 AM CST to 4 PM CST.

* WINDS...Northwest 15 to 20 mph with gusts up to 30 mph.

* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...As low as 15 percent.

* TEMPERATURES...Up to 88.

* IMPACTS...Rapid spread of wildfire on drying grasses and brush
is possibly Friday.
properties.instruction:

are forecast to occur. Listen for later forecasts and possible

properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued March 7 at 1:42PM PST by NWS Seattle WA
properties.description:
ESFSEW

A series of storm systems will spread moderate to heavy rainfall
across Western Washington this weekend and into early next week.
Storm total rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches are possible across
the Olympic Peninsula. Snow levels near 2500-3000 ft may limit
runoff amounts. This amount of prolonged rainfall has the potential
to push the Skokomish River into flood stage.

Please monitor the latest river forecasts from the National Weather
Service for additional information.

properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued March 7 at 2:11PM CST by NWS Chicago IL
properties.description:
ESFLOT

A period of steady rainfall is expected to move into the area on
Friday, lingering into the evening. Widespread rainfall amounts up
to one inch are possible across northeast Illinois and northwest
Indiana, with amounts of 1-2 inches possible in isolated areas.
Dormant vegetation and elevated soil moisture conditions will reduce
infiltration and allow for much of this rainfall to runoff into area
streams and rivers.

Ensemble river forecast guidance indicates the possibility of
multiple rivers reaching bankfull due to this rainfall. Urban areas
and poor drainage areas may also experience areas of standing water.
While widespread flooding is not likely, a few river locations may
near flood stage by this weekend.

This outlook means that elevated water levels and potential impacts
are possible, but not yet certain. Persons should closely monitor
forecasts including the possibility of flood watches, warnings, and
advisories.

An update to this outlook will be issued by tomorrow morning.

properties.areaDesc: Burleigh, ND; Morton, ND
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued March 6 at 3:01PM CST by NWS Bismarck ND
properties.description:
ESFBIS

Given the recent cold weather, the Missouri River has again been
forming ice below Garrison Dam. Thus far, ice has filled the
recently cleared portion of the Missouri River from roughly Apple
Creek Wildlife Management Area to about three-fourths of a mile
upstream of where 12th street southeast turns into Oahe Bend. This
would roughly be equal to a little less than five miles of new ice
in the river.

The upstream edge of immobile ice as of Wednesday morning was
roughly three and a half miles downstream of Fort Abraham Lincoln
and Fox Island. While the future rate of ice formation is difficult
to predict, forecast overnight lows in the single digits for both
Thursday and Friday mornings will continue to encourage ice
formation. It should be expected that the upstream edge of
continuous ice on the river will migrate upstream. Based on how much
ice has already been put in place, it is possible that the upstream
edge of continuous ice will reach the Fox Island area before warmer
weather enters the area on Friday. By late Saturday, warmer weather
will once again reverse this process and start removing ice.

Importantly, pre-ice river levels were about 3.5 feet below that
observed prior to last week's ice jam due to already planned lower
releases out of Garrison Dam. This suggests that a return to water
levels experienced in late February is not likely.

NWSheadline: MISSOURI RIVER IS ONCE AGAIN MAKING ICE
